{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530882"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:10:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:10:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14573"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14573"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.05,0.06,0.03,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58307"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7266"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14573"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43747"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44968"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58307"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a history of recurrent nosebleeds since childhood. She reports that her father and sister also experience frequent nosebleeds. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple small, red, blanching lesions on her lips and oral mucosa (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Von Willebrand disease","Haemophilia","Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis","Hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia\u003C/strong\u003E (HHT) is an autosomal dominant disorder characterised by recurrent bleeding, mucocutaneous telangiectasias, and arteriovenous malformations. The presence of recurrent nosebleeds, family history, and visible telangiectasias on the lips and oral mucosa strongly suggest this diagnosis. Diagnosis can be made clinically based on criteria including spontaneous recurrent epistaxis, multiple telangiectasias, visceral lesions, and first-degree relative with HHT. Genetic testing can also be performed to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with HHT require screening for visceral arteriovenous malformations, particularly in the lungs, brain, and liver, as these can lead to serious complications. Telangiectasias throughout the gastrointestinal tract may lead to recurrent gastrointestinal bleeding, which together with epistaxis can contribute to iron deficiency anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon Willebrand disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited bleeding disorder caused by deficient or defective von Willebrand factor, leading to impaired platelet adhesion. While it can cause epistaxis, it typically presents with easy bruising, prolonged bleeding after minor injuries, and heavy menstrual periods. It does not cause telangiectasias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilia\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-linked recessive bleeding disorder primarily affecting males, caused by deficiency of either factor VIII or IX. While it can cause bleeding, this typically affects deep tissues and joints. Additionally, it does not cause telangiectasias and the inheritance pattern does not fit this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a systemic vasculitis that typically presents with upper respiratory tract symptoms, pulmonary infiltrates, and glomerulonephritis. While it can cause epistaxis, it does not have a hereditary pattern or cause telangiectasias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E is an acquired autoimmune disorder characterised by isolated thrombocytopenia. While it can cause mucosal bleeding, it does not cause telangiectasias and is not a hereditary condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia is an autosomal dominant disorder associated with recurrent epistaxis, mucocutaneous telangiectasias, and arteriovenous malformations.","Complications can include gastrointestinal bleeding, iron deficiency anaemia and arteriovenous malformations."],"references":["Faughnan ME, Mager JJ, Hetts SW, et al. Second International Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia. Ann Intern Med. 2020;173(12):989-1001. Available at: https://hhtguidelines.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Second-International-HHT-Guidelines-Annals-2020.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43747"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14573"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21113"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21113"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https: